NEW YORK, March 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S.-listed Chinese companies roughly traded lower on Friday with all the top 10 stocks by weight in the S&P U.S. Listed China 50 index ending the day on a downbeat note. Shares of Yum China Holdings and Bilibili slumped 15.51 percent and 12.27 percent, respectively,leading the losses in the top 10 stocks in the index. Shares of BeiGene and XPeng tumbled 12.21 percent and 12.12 percent, respectively, also among the worst performers in the top 10 stocks. U.S. stocks dropped on Friday as the ongoing Russia-Ukraine conflict continues to unnerve investors. The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 229.88 points, or 0.69 percent, to 32,944.19. The S&P 500 slid 55.21 points, or 1.30 percent, to 4,204.31. The Nasdaq Composite Index decreased 286.15 points, or 2.18 percent, to 12,843.81. The Cboe Volatility Index, widely considered as the best fear gauge in the stock market, rose 1.72 percent to 30.75. As of Thursday, the S&P U.S. Listed China 50 index, which is designed to track the performance of the 50 largest Chinese companies listed on U.S. exchanges by total market cap, stood at 2,181.96, marking an 18.86-percent slide for the month-to-date returns and a 26.74-percent loss for the year-to-date returns.  â– 